
The Core Idea
Two pointers on strings means you place one pointer at the left and one at the right and move them towards each other based on a condition.
s = "racecar"
      ↑     ↑
    left   right

compare s[left] and s[right]
if they match → move both inward
if they don't → you have your answer

Pattern 1 — Palindrome Check (the foundation)
Problem: is a string a palindrome?
javapublic boolean isPalindrome(String s) {
    int left  = 0;
    int right = s.length() - 1;

    while (left < right) {              // stop when they meet in the middle
        if (s.charAt(left) != s.charAt(right)) {
            return false;               // mismatch — not a palindrome
        }
        left++;                         // move inward
        right--;
    }

    return true;
}
Trace on "racecar":
left=0  right=6  → r == r ✅ move inward
left=1  right=5  → a == a ✅ move inward
left=2  right=4  → c == c ✅ move inward
left=3  right=3  → left < right is false → stop
return true ✅
Trace on "hello":
left=0  right=4  → h == o ❌
return false ✅

Pattern 2 — Reverse a String In Place
javapublic void reverseString(char[] s) {
    int left  = 0;
    int right = s.length - 1;

    while (left < right) {
        // swap
        char temp  = s[left];
        s[left]    = s[right];
        s[right]   = temp;

        left++;
        right--;
    }
}
Trace on ['h','e','l','l','o']:
left=0 right=4 → swap h,o → ['o','e','l','l','h']
left=1 right=3 → swap e,l → ['o','l','l','e','h']
left=2 right=2 → left < right false → stop
result: "olleh" ✅

Pattern 3 — Valid Palindrome II (the tricky interview version)
Problem: given a string, can you remove at most one character and still have a palindrome?
This is where two pointer gets interesting.
javapublic boolean validPalindrome(String s) {
    int left  = 0;
    int right = s.length() - 1;

    while (left < right) {
        if (s.charAt(left) != s.charAt(right)) {
            // mismatch found — try skipping left char OR right char
            // if EITHER gives a palindrome → true
            return isPalindrome(s, left + 1, right)
                || isPalindrome(s, left, right - 1);
        }
        left++;
        right--;
    }

    return true; // no mismatch at all — already a palindrome
}

// helper — checks palindrome between two indices
private boolean isPalindrome(String s, int left, int right) {
    while (left < right) {
        if (s.charAt(left) != s.charAt(right)) return false;
        left++;
        right--;
    }
    return true;
}
Trace on "abca":
left=0 right=3 → a == a ✅ move inward
left=1 right=2 → b == c ❌ mismatch

try skip left:  isPalindrome("abca", 2, 2) → "c" → true ✅
return true ✅
Trace on "abcda":
left=0 right=4 → a == a ✅
left=1 right=3 → b == d ❌ mismatch

try skip left:  isPalindrome("abcda", 2, 3) → "cd" → c==d? ❌
try skip right: isPalindrome("abcda", 1, 2) → "bc" → b==c? ❌
return false ✅

